<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTD/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
    Minimum-surface entitlements for the app target.

    The only declared entitlement is the default per-app Keychain
    access group (`$(DEVELOPMENT_TEAM).$(CFBundleIdentifier)`).
    Using `$(DEVELOPMENT_TEAM).` instead of `$(AppIdentifierPrefix)`
    avoids a build-time provisioning-profile lookup: Xcode can expand
    `$(DEVELOPMENT_TEAM)` from the build settings directly, so
    `CODE_SIGN_ALLOW_ENTITLEMENTS_MODIFICATION` is not needed.

    Making the default explicit pins the PAT's storage scope: a future
    share / notification-center extension added to the project would
    otherwise silently expand its own Keychain access-group set and
    gain visibility into the parent app's credentials without anyone
    reviewing the change.

    Both `$(DEVELOPMENT_TEAM)` and `$(CFBundleIdentifier)` are
    resolved by Xcode at build time so a future bundle-id or team-id
    change flows through automatically without a separate edit here.

    Cross-extension PAT sharing is intentionally out of scope — see
    ADR-0012 §PAT storage. Any future extension that needs Keychain
    access must either run outside the app's access group (a new
    entitlement row here) or surface its own PAT-entry UX; it must
    not inherit the viewer's PAT silently.

    Reference: security-review SR-20260419-029.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>keychain-access-groups</key>
    <array>
        <string>$(DEVELOPMENT_TEAM).$(CFBundleIdentifier)</string>
    </array>
</dict>
</plist>
